                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPORT BRIEFS
                                                            
	Black Caps recall Oram  Wellington: Allrounders James Franklin and Jacob Oram have been recalled to the New Zealand side after recovering from injuries, while uncapped opening batsman Tim McIntosh has been brought in for the Tests against the West Indies.  The 29-year-old left-handed McIntosh replaces Aaron Redmond at the top of the order.
  Pace bowlers Chris Martin and Tim Southee have also been dropped along with middle-order batsman Peter Fulton. The first Test in Dunedin begins on Thursday.   The Squad: Daniel Vettori (Capt.), Jamie How, Tim McIntosh, Daniel Flynn, Ross Taylor, Jesse Ryder, Jacob Oram, Brendon McCullum, James Franklin, Mark Gillespie, Iain O rsquo;Brien, Jeetan Patel.    
	 Dhoni cover  Ranchi: Team India captain Mahendra Singh Dhoni will get enhanced security cover with Jharkhand CM Shibu Soren directing the police to ensure that armed men, if required commandos, were deployed to guard him.    
	 Wisden sale  London: Bloomsbury, the publisher of J.K. Rowling rsquo;s lsquo;Harry Potter rsquo; series, has bought famous cricket publication, lsquo;Wisden rsquo;.  The purchase price for a business with just a staff of four is ldquo;not material rdquo;, said Bloomsbury. ldquo;But it wants to capitalise on cricket's booming popularity, particularly in India and other Asian countries. rdquo;    
	 Vishy function  Chennai: Indian captain Mahendra Singh Dhoni and his team will felicitate world chess champion Viswanathan Anand on the opening day of their first cricket Test against England, beginning here from Thursday.    
	 Ranjeet best  New Delhi: Ranjeet Virali Murugesan justified his top billing by crowning himself national champion after taming giant-killer Sriram Balaji in straight sets in the final of the DSCL senior men rsquo;s national tennis championship on Saturday.    
	 Evra ban  London: Manchester United defender Patrice Evra was banned for four matches and fined pound;15,000 by the Football Association (FA) on Friday for his part in a fracas at Chelsea.    
	 Mann tied 19th  Ho Chi Minh City: Baaz Mann was at the tied 19th spot after the penultimate round of the $500,000 Vietnam Masters here Saturday. Digvijay Singh was at tied 31st. Amandeep Johl is at tied 26th after carding an identical 73. Rahil Gangjee (72) and S.S.P. Chowrasia (71) are at tied 43rd.     
	 Shamim wins  Jamshedpur: Shamim Khan continued his fine form and turned in an even-par 70 in the final round to win the Tata Open here Saturday.  After leading the field for the last two days, Shamim finally emerged on top with a tournament total of 10-under 272 to register his third professional victory.  
